<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-06T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-06T16:00:00-05:00" n="326" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d326">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">824.6363 ST 2/202: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in Bolivia</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Caldwell</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-06T16:00:00-05:00">December 6, 1937—4
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>32. Your telegrams 70, December 3, 2 p.m., and 71, December 3, 3 p.m. The
                            Department is of the opinion that, until you are informed of the
                            definite decision by the Junta, you should take no further action in the
                            case except to follow and report upon important developments. Air mail
                            instruction follows.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>